(*
  G++ grammar, v0.6.0 — a delta over spec/grammar-v0.5.1.ebnf. Every
  production not listed here is unchanged.

  This file and the Godog feature suite under features/ are together the
  authoritative specification of G++.
*)

(* -------------------- Variants: existentials + full GADTs --------------- *)

VariantDecl = identifier [ TypeParameters ] [ Parameters ] [ Type ] .

(*
  - The optional TypeParameters declare BOUNDED EXISTENTIAL type
    variables: `Packed[A fmt.Stringer, B error](x A, y A, e B)`. Every
    existential variable must carry an interface bound (not `any`), must
    be used by at least one field, and must not appear in the variant's
    result type. Lowering ERASES AT THE BOUNDARY: struct fields and the
    lowered constructor are typed at the bound, and match binders bind at
    the bound. Two fields sharing an existential variable lose the
    same-dynamic-type fact (documented). An unbounded variable is a
    compile error: Go cannot express a match arm generic in a hidden
    type — give the variable an interface bound or store the composition
    instead.
  - The optional result Type (GADT pinning) now admits ARBITRARY type
    expressions per position: `Expr[[]T]`, `Pair[A, B]`, `*T`,
    cross-position uses like `Foo[U, T]`. A variant struct's type
    parameters are exactly the enum type parameters OCCURRING anywhere in
    the result arguments (enum order, enum constraints). Refinement is
    learned by structural unification of the result arguments against the
    scrutinee's type arguments and applied to every mismatched conversion
    boundary in the arm. When the scrutinee's argument is a bare type
    parameter and the variant's argument is composite, Go's erasure
    cannot name the arm's case head: the variant still counts toward
    exhaustiveness but an explicit arm for it is an error (cover it with
    `case _:`).
*)

(* ------------------------------- Folds ----------------------------------- *)

(*
  Every enum derives, BY DEFAULT, a one-level fold in its own package:

    type <Enum>Cases[<enum tparams>, R any] struct { <one func field per
        variant, named as written, params = the variant's lowered field
        types, returning R; bare variants func() R> }
    func Fold[<enum tparams>, R any](e <Enum>[…], cs <Enum>Cases[…, R]) R

  The fold function follows the v0.5.1 naming rule (bare `Fold` when
  unique in the package; colliders — including a second deriving enum —
  all fall back to <Enum>Fold). `//gpp:derive off` on the enum
  declaration suppresses derivation; an enum whose variant result
  arguments leave a struct type parameter undetermined under the
  identity instantiation derives nothing (same erasure wall as above).
  Fold dispatches ALL variants — it is instantiation-generic and does no
  GADT filtering.
*)

(* ----------------------------- Delegation -------------------------------- *)

FieldDecl = IdentifierList Type [ "delegate" ] [ Tag ]
          | EmbeddedField [ Tag ] .

(*
  - `delegate` is a contextual identifier claimed only after a NAMED
    field's type inside a struct body — a bare identifier there is never
    valid Go. `x delegate` (a field of type delegate) and `Store
    delegate` (a field Store of type delegate) keep their Go meanings.
  - The field's type must be an interface. The outer type gains a
    generated value-receiver forwarding method for every interface
    method it does not otherwise declare (authored anywhere in the
    package, promoted from embedding, or previously generated — all
    count as overrides). Two delegate fields offering the same method is
    an error naming both. A delegate field is NOT embedded: no promotion
    happens beyond the generated forwarders.
*)
